#: ../../callbacks.md:1
msgid "Javascript callbacks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:3
msgid "*Changed in Koffi 2.4*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:6
msgid ""
"The function `koffi.proto()` was introduced in Koffi 2.4, it was called "
"`koffi.callback()` in earlier versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:9
msgid "Callback types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:11
msgid ""
"In order to pass a JS function to a C function expecting a callback, you "
"must first create a callback type with the expected return type and "
"parameters. The syntax is similar to the one used to load functions from "
"a shared library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:24
msgid ""
"Once your callback type is declared, you can use a pointer to it in "
"struct definitions, as function parameters and/or return types, or to "
"call/decode function pointers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:27
msgid "Callbacks **have changed in version 2.0**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:29
msgid ""
"In Koffi 1.x, callbacks were defined in a way that made them usable "
"directly as parameter and return types, obscuring the underlying pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:31
msgid ""
"Now, you must use them through a pointer: `void CallIt(CallbackType "
"func)` in Koffi 1.x becomes `void CallIt(CallbackType *func)` in version "
"2.0 and newer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:33
msgid "Consult the [migration guide](migration.md) for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:36
msgid "Transient and registered callbacks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:38
msgid ""
"Koffi only uses predefined static trampolines, and does not need to "
"generate code at runtime, which makes it compatible with platforms with "
"hardened W^X migitations (such as PaX mprotect). However, this imposes "
"some restrictions on the maximum number of callbacks, and their duration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:40
msgid "Thus, Koffi distinguishes two callback modes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:42
msgid ""
"[Transient callbacks](#transient-callbacks) can only be called while the "
"C function they are passed to is running, and are invalidated when it "
"returns. If the C function calls the callback later, the behavior is "
"undefined, though Koffi tries to detect such cases. If it does, an "
"exception will be thrown, but this is no guaranteed. However, they are "
"simple to use, and don't require any special handling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:43
msgid ""
"[Registered callbacks](#registered-callbacks) can be called at any time, "
"but they must be manually registered and unregistered. A limited number "
"of registered callbacks can exist at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:45
msgid ""
"You need to specify the correct [calling convention](functions.md"
"#calling-conventions) on x86 platforms, or the behavior is undefined "
"(Node will probably crash). Only *cdecl* and *stdcall* callbacks are "
"supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:47
msgid "Transient callbacks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:49
msgid ""
"Use transient callbacks when the native C function only needs to call "
"them while it runs (e.g. qsort, progress callback, `sqlite3_exec`). Here "
"is a small example with the C part and the JS part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:85
msgid "Registered callbacks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:87
msgid "*New in Koffi 2.0 (explicit this binding in Koffi 2.2)*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:89
msgid ""
"Use registered callbacks when the function needs to be called at a later "
"time (e.g. log handler, event handler, `fopencookie/funopen`). Call "
"`koffi.register(func, type)` to register a callback function, with two "
"arguments: the JS function, and the callback type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:91
msgid ""
"When you are done, call `koffi.unregister()` (with the value returned by "
"`koffi.register()`) to release the slot. A maximum of 1024 callbacks can "
"exist at the same time. Failure to do so will leak the slot, and "
"subsequent registrations may fail (with an exception) once all slots are "
"used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:93
msgid "The example below shows how to register and unregister delayed callbacks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:134
msgid ""
"Starting *with Koffi 2.2*, you can optionally specify the `this` value "
"for the function as the first argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:148
msgid "Special considerations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:150
msgid "Decoding pointer arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:152
msgid "*New in Koffi 2.2, changed in Koffi 2.3*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:154
msgid ""
"Koffi does not have enough information to convert callback pointer "
"arguments to an appropriate JS value. In this case, your JS function will"
" receive an opaque *External* object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:156
msgid ""
"You can pass this value through to another C function that expects a "
"pointer of the same type, or you can use `koffi.decode()` to decode it "
"into something you can use in Javascript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:158
msgid ""
"Some arguments are optional and this function can be called in several "
"ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:160
msgid "`koffi.decode(value, type)`: no offset, expect NUL-terminated strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:161
msgid ""
"`koffi.decode(value, offset, type)`: explicit offset to add to the "
"pointer before decoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:163
msgid "The following example sorts an array of strings (in-place) with `qsort()`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:186
msgid ""
"There is also an optional ending `length` argument that you can use in "
"two cases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:188
msgid ""
"Use it to give the number of bytes to decode in non-NUL terminated "
"strings: `koffi.decode(value, 'char *', 5)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:189
msgid ""
"Decode consecutive values into an array. For example, here is how you can"
" decode an array with 3 float values: `koffi.decode(value, 'float', 3)`. "
"This is equivalent to `koffi.decode(value, koffi.array('float', 3))`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:192
msgid ""
"In Koffi 2.2 and earlier versions, the length argument is only used to "
"decode strings and is ignored otherwise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:195
msgid "Asynchronous callbacks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:197
msgid "*New in Koffi 2.2.2*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:199
msgid ""
"JS execution is inherently single-threaded, so JS callbacks must run on "
"the main thread. There are two ways you may want to call a callback "
"function from another thread:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:201
msgid "Call the callback from an asynchronous FFI call (e.g. `waitpid.async`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:202
msgid "Inside a synchronous FFI call, pass the callback to another thread"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:204
msgid ""
"In both cases, Koffi will queue the call back to JS to run on the main "
"thread, as soon as the JS event loop has a chance to run (for example "
"when you await a promise)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:207
msgid ""
"Be careful, you can easily get into a deadlock situation if you call a "
"callback from a secondary thread and your main thread never lets the JS "
"event loop run (for example, if the main thread waits for the secondary "
"thread to finish something itself)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:210
msgid "Handling of exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:212
msgid ""
"If an exception happens inside the JS callback, the C API will receive 0 "
"or NULL (depending on the return value type)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../callbacks.md:214
msgid ""
"Handle the exception yourself (with try/catch) if you need to handle "
"exceptions differently."
msgstr ""

